Is there a black box in your car?
While American road designers are trying to find money to repair a crumbling highway system, many are beginning to see the solution in a small black box neatly mounted on your car’s dashboard.
These devices, tracking every mile a motorist drives and transmitting this information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system undertaken by Washington and the state’s planning authorities.
Usually, the boring arena of highway planning unexpectedly spawned intense debates and colorful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you drive and even possibly where you drive them — and then use that information to compile tax bills.
The Tea Party is in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of privacy issues.
And while Congress can’t agree on whether to continue or not, a few states aren’t going to wait.
They are reflecting on how to move to a system where drivers pay for every mile of road they drive over the next decade.
Thousands of motorists have already taken these black boxes for testing, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
“It’s not an issue on which we may have a choice,” said Hassan Ichrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to begin tracking the state’s mileage by every California motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay these taxes.
Technology already exists for this.
The need for this is exacerbated by the lack of funds from the Government Highway Construction Fund, financed by taxes that Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars travel more than a mile per gallon.
The federal tax, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not been raised in 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax by even one cent at high gasoline prices.
“The gasoline tax is simply impossible to save,” said Lee Mannich, an expert on transportation policy at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices were recently installed on cars to test the false payment system.
“It will be the best alternative in the long run,” he said.
Boredom is called a false user fee.
It is not surprising that this idea attracts urban liberals, because with the help of taxes it will be possible to change the nature of travel to reduce road congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planners in California are looking into the system in developing strategies to meet the targets set by the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
However, House of Representatives member Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the chamber’s transport committee, said he also sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Supporters of the free market at Reason are also thrilled that drivers will be forced to pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that’s going to go into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of political affairs at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in 2011 called on Congress to move toward a false payment.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved some 10,000 vehicles.
However, House leaders rejected the proposal because of fears of rural lawmakers representing voters who often have to travel many miles in their daily lives to get to work or the city.
Several states and cities, however, follow this path on their own.
The greatest enthusiasm is shown in the state of Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are involved in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon pay the state for mileage instead of gasoline tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
It is being considered in New York.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with the participation of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport departments of 17 East Coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how they can make these changes.
This concept has not received universal recognition.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer vehicles were recently fitted with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track their every move.
“Worrying about big brother and stuff like that is a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and efficiency management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn’t what people wanted.
As the tests were underway, the American Civil Liberties Union in Nevada warned on its website: “It will be easy to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices.”
There is no need to create a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to keep records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of several states where difficult searches are underway for low-cost technology that would allow state authorities to keep track of miles traveled by car, but without information about the location and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more at ease.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, the company did not assist in collecting state taxes.
It sought to enter the emerging market of a type of auto insurance, in which drivers pay on the basis of mileage.
But the devices she’s testing attract road designers because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information periodically downloaded via a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and track their location,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There were a few major errors in some of these state pilot programs.
There are much less expensive and less obsessive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with providing drivers with a variety of options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can completely abandon the device, deciding instead to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state travel.
Elsewhere, they hope to sell the idea to a wary public, forcing the devices to do more, not less.
In New York, transport officials are looking to develop a taxable device that will also accept parking meter payments, provide “pay-as-you-go” insurance, and collect real-time speed data pools from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists will be attracted to participate in the benefits that will be offered to them,” – stated in the document of urban design.
Some transport system designers, however, are wondering whether all the talk of wrong payment is simply a huge distraction.
The San Francisco Bay Area City Transportation Commission officials say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the trust fund for highway construction by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on hybrid car drivers and others whose vehicles do not use a lot of gasoline to pay their fair share.
“There’s no need for radical surgery when all you need to do is take an aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the Legislation and Public Relations Commission.
If we do, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a lot of other things.
EU prepares measures to support Ukraine in case of economic pressure from Russia
The European Union has a contingency plan to provide Ukraine with gas, as well as to reach an agreement with the IMF on an emergency loan, if Russia takes any measures in response to the possible signing of an association agreement between the EU and Ukraine at the Vilnius summit.
A stand-by loan is being negotiated with the IMF, and another EU official directly involved in the negotiations added that their goal is to conclude an agreement in the near future.
At the same time, in addition to a potential loan from the IMF, Ukraine can receive 610 million euros from the European Union itself.
Analysts interviewed by Reuters doubt that Ukraine and the IMF are able to overcome long-standing disagreements on funding terms.
He does not believe in the possibility of reforms necessary to receive aid, and the international rating agency S&P, which on Friday lowered the sovereign rating of Ukraine by one degree - to "B-" with "B".
However, EU representatives say that the IMF can show flexibility in terms of lending, taking into account the circumstances of Ukraine.
In addition to the country’s financial support plan, the EU has a back-up option to provide Ukraine with gas, the vast majority of which now comes from Russia.
Perhaps it will be gas from the Nord Stream or reverse from Slovakia.
The latter, according to officials, is the most possible and acceptable way in the event that Russia “isolates” Ukraine.
Analysts believe that this method of reversing supplies to Ukraine can only be used for a few weeks, and will likely lead to a decrease in supplies to other regions.
“There are negotiations between EU countries and Ukrainians on how to create favorable conditions so that Ukraine can import gas from other sources, not from Russia, or from the same source, but through other routes,” the source added.
Russia out of the fight for pollution of cities by cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of large cities have been observed in most megacities of the world since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about their reconstruction and expansion of highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for road trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
The example of Singapore is widely known, where a strict quota of the increase in the number of private cars is introduced, and the right to purchase them is purchased at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times higher than the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced a fee for entering the city center.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, so-called green zones are introduced, where only cars with a certain eco-class are allowed to enter, which also use high-quality fuel (including biofuels or electric vehicles).
Beijing’s Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved a “five-year clean air plan” worth about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion) in 2012.
According to Lee Kunsheng, director of the transport pollution control department of the Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau, the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, to increase the number of private cars to no more than 6 million (currently 5.2 million), and to increase fuel use by no more than 5% per vehicle.
According to the agency, now motor vehicles in Beijing are responsible for 22.5 percent of the total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program is the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, the urban measures of the "green five-year plan" include the accelerated compared to the rest of the country transition to electric fuel standards, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and marking of cars and fuel, the restriction on the entry of cars into the central part of the city, the ban on the use of obsolete vehicles (in addition, the creation of incentive financial programs to replace old cars with electric or hybrid vehicles).
Among the automotive innovations of Beijing also includes a ban on all private cars to drive within the fifth transport ring (there are six in the capital of the PRC) one day a week (relevant information is contained in the license plate of the vehicle), as well as the issuance of license plates for cars based on the lottery (for example, in 2011, the first year of operation of the lottery, the total number of license plates in the third part of the license plate).
According to the current state program “Environmental Protection 2012-2020”, the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Natural Resources, in 2011, “mobile sources” accounted for 41% of all emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
Russia is just beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
Mikhail Blinkin, Director of the Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy of the HSE, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for road trips are obviously unpopular, they can be adopted by society only under the condition of their full universality.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem associated with the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters weakly sensitive to any regulatory influences - service and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is at least 200 thousand (about 5% of the total number of Moscow's fleet).
Recently, urbanists from the ECOM center in St. Petersburg prepared a study that analyzes the balance of urban areas between residential development, road surface area and the number of vehicles.
The main conclusions of the researchers: the city center is provided with roads twice less than required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking spaces, but car storage, not to expand, but to reduce the roadway (so that the streets become more pedestrian-friendly), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the territory of the historical center protection zone (a total area of about 3,212 hectares, covering a number of central areas of the city).
Penalties for unauthorized street trade in Vologda will increase at times
According to the city authorities, the increase in the amount of fines will help to restore order in Vologda and free the streets from natural tents and trays.
Most street vendors do not pay taxes, and the products they sell often do not pass the proper sanitary control.
And this means that the health of wetlands is at risk.
Thus, the lower limit of the fine for citizens for unauthorized trade from November will increase six times - from 500 rubles to 3000 rubles, the press service of the Administration of Vologda.
Goldman Sachs Warns of Risks to Russian Economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks to Russia’s main driver of fragile economic growth: consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payment on unsecured consumer loans and mass reductions of workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed down, but rather that the structure of that growth.
Recently, it is fully driven by consumption, which almost does not reduce turnover,” said the chief economist of Goldman Sachs on Russia Clemens Grafe, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
The nominal growth of wages in Russia is about 10%.
With an inflation rate of 6%, it will be able to meet future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so they are likely to optimize personnel costs.
Today, we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - said Mr. Grafe.
Companies are facing a decline in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to layoffs and rising unemployment.
Russian business cannot raise wages, comments chief economist of Barclays Capital for Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment is near historic lows, competition for workers is high.
In order to lure employees from the sidelines or keep current ones, employers have to raise wages.
Consumption in Russia is supported by the very rapid growth of borrowing.
According to Mr. Grafe, due to the extremely high rates of consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the country's economy.
"We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of borrowing, the money does not diverge in the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments," the economist said.
But the problem is that Goldman Sachs expects a rise in defaults on unsecured loans.
They are taken mostly by poor people who have nothing to provide for security.
The interest rates for such loans are high.
As a result, they are not returned more often,” Mr. Grafe said.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payment on unsecured loans.
The Director of the Banking Institute of HSE Vasily Solodkov already sees signs of a brewing banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, lacking access to cheap resources such as the state banks, were forced to attract the funds of the population at high interest rates.
In response, state banks took the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rate, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If state banks do not refuse dumping, Russia is threatened with a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks, the economist considers a harbinger of mass collapse.
“State banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was originally not designed for a systemic crisis,” the head of the institute warns.
But consumption growth will slow down without a crisis of non-payment, according to the investment bank, due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
Part of the impact on consumption will be mitigated by the freezing of tariffs on natural monopolies (and, as a consequence, by a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and the prerequisites for this are not yet - see the certificate), the growth of consumption will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is confident.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still the fall in oil prices,” he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to shrink at an oil price below $ 90 / barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks began to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting,” said Clemens Grafe.
The interest rate policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, it affects only interbank lending rates.
“For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes,” Clemens Grafe said.
The money received at the auctions of the Central Bank, banks use not for lending to the economy, and to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate drops, the exchange rate changes immediately, this means that the funds are trying to go to speculation against the ruble.
“Sooner or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy does not work,” Mr. Grafe said and reminded that the state plans to release the ruble into the “free float” by the end of 2015.
But we will either have to do it sooner or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he believes.
According to him, the ruble is now artificially overestimated by 10%.
There is only one way to get weak, the expert concludes.
But if the Central Bank plunges in the financiers at least a shadow of doubt that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can bring down the ruble much more.
