Snowden is ready to “collaborate” with Germany on the issue of US intelligence
Edward Snowden, a U.S. intelligence whistleblower, said he was willing to go to Berlin to testify to the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director, Keith Alexander, were unable to answer questions about their activities.
German lawmaker Hans-Christian Ströbele met with Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he was granted asylum to discuss his testimony in Germany.
A letter from Mr. Snowden, who was presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, said: “Although the result of my efforts was clearly positive, my government continues to treat dissent as treason and seeks to criminalize political statements with criminal charges that offer no protection whatsoever.”
But telling the truth is not a crime.
In the letter, Mr. Snowden said he believed that support from the international community could convince the U.S. government to drop criminal charges against him.
The charges brought by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany’s interior minister, told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is willing to speak to German officials, we will find ways to make this possible.”
Relations between the United States and Germany have become tense after allegations that the NSA tapped Chancellor Angela Merkel’s phone.
Thomas Opperman, a lawmaker who heads a parliamentary group overseeing intelligence, said that if there is an opportunity to listen to Mr. Snowden as a witness, “without endangering him or destroying relations with the United States completely,” it should be used.
Mr. Ströbele, a Green German MP, posted his photo with Mr. Snowden on Twitter.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Ströbele said that, according to the lawyer of the former NSA contractor, Mr. Snowden could not return to Russia if he left.
If Mr. Snowden were testifying in Germany, he would need guarantees that he would be “safe” there, the MP said.
Mr. Snowden said in his letter that he faced a “tough and ongoing” persecution campaign that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was encouraged by the global response to “his political statements.”
Citizens around the world, as well as high-ranking officials — including in the United States — found exposing the uncontrolled system of all-pervasive surveillance useful to society.
The letter offers to cooperate with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are resolved”.
Frontier Airlines will charge a fee for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board its flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although their announcement on Wednesday said passengers could keep the entire bank.
The new hand luggage charge applies to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee was paid in advance, and $100 if travelers paid only when they were on board.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said a $100 fee should force passengers to take care of the payment in advance.
“We don’t want to charge for it,” she said.
Airlines began charging for the first and second bags to be checked in in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges are stuffed as much as they can in hand luggage placed in the upper luggage compartments, which is why there is often not enough space in these compartments.
Fees are one way to get passengers to carry less on board.
O'Malley said this new fee isn't really about making money.
The fact is that the most loyal Frontier customers say that finding a place in the upper luggage compartments is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in the queue at the entrance to the Frontier flight may be able to carry the bag for free, while the next passenger in the queue may pay $100 for the same bag.
O’Malley said the change in procedures on the website and Frontier’s check-in desks is meant to ensure passengers are aware of the collection before they get to the boarding gate.
Frontier’s new hand luggage charge will not start until the summer, although the date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage charges and other charges, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who need this service have to pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines charge enough money to cover flight costs after years of losses.
However, most of them did not concern the fees for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first hand luggage charge three years ago, and another Allegiant Air discounter later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
According to his assessment in a December 2011 report, the hand luggage fee brings Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former top manager of Midwest Airlines, had recently flown a Spirit flight, and he was interested in what he would find at the boarding gate when passengers faced an unusual collection of Spirit for hand luggage.
“The landing process was the smoothest I’ve seen in my airline career,” he said.
I expected to see the gnashing of teeth and the appearance of a fight at the exit to the landing.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing went fast.”
Frontier also follows Spirit in terms of a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda, or juice.
Frontier said passengers who receive soda or juice could keep the entire pot and that a coffee pot would be provided free of charge.
It will continue to distribute water free of charge.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for drinks in 2008, but dropped it seven months later after passengers began complaining and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier’s hand luggage charge initiative, where passengers don’t buy tickets directly from the airline, is its latest measure to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket vendors, such as Orbitz, between $10 and $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than contacting a travel online agency.
However, Frontier went further than anyone in this area.
In September, it began giving twice as many frequent flyer bonus miles to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, it cut the premium mileage to 25 percent of the mileage.
For example, a 1,000-mile trip with Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would get 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a seat in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in her hometown of Denver, but her business is shrinking and becoming unprofitable.
Revenue fell 9 percent and flight capacity fell nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
The Republic is trying to correct Frontier's finances as part of the airline's sale.
NSA blames ‘internal error’, not hackers for shutting down site
The secretive National Security Agency said Friday evening that shutting down their site for a few hours caused a technical failure, not hackers, as claimed on the network.
"NSA.gov was unavailable for several hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update," the intelligence agency said in an official email.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Claims that the downtime was caused by a distributed denial-of-service [DDoS] attack are false.
Earlier this evening, online server monitoring systems registered that the NSA website had not worked for at least six hours, and the site is still unavailable to some users.
Earlier, an NSA spokesman told ABC News that the agency’s internal secret network had “not” been hacked.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesman said.
At least one online group of hackers-activists said it was responsible for disabling the NSA website through a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to flood the target site with traffic until the servers are overloaded and the site fails.
The tactics of hackers are relatively simple, and the attacks are not designed to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
The previously top-secret NSA, once dubbed “No Such Agency,” has been in the spotlight in recent months after a string of revelations about its extensive surveillance programs abroad and domestically — all in response to secret NSA files stolen from the agency and published by a frustrated former NSA employee, Edward S.
The growing controversy around the agency has sparked speculation that today’s incident was the result of targeted hackers’ actions.
Bombardier’s profit decreases with falling deliveries and the number of orders for aircraft
Bombardier Corporation, a Canadian aircraft and train manufacturer, reported on Thursday a 15 percent reduction in net profit amid a decline in third-quarter orders and deliveries and contract issues at its rail division.
The Montreal-based Bombardier company also did not release any flight test data for its latest CSeries aircraft and did not provide new information on whether ambitious plans to put the aircraft into commercial operation by next September will be implemented.
After the first flight of the prototype aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, it flew only three more times, which raises questions about whether the test phase is on schedule.
The results did not meet the forecasts and led to a fall in shares of more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerxen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, cut his valuation from “above the mid-market” to “mid-market” on Thursday because of the belief that stock growth is limited in the next quarter or two.
“Although the decline in aircraft shipments was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed by the transport department’s profit figures,” Doerksen said in a stock market review.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we assume that the market will become more skeptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to win a place in the lower price segment of the market, which is now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype of the aircraft was presented in March and first flew in September after several months of delay.
However, there are not too many firm orders for the CSeries so far – 177, as potential buyers are waiting for the results of flight tests to test the company’s claims about fuel efficiency and potential economy of the new liner.
There are currently 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief Executive Pierre Baudouin was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft was put into commercial operation.
On Thursday, leaders also assured analysts and the media that the program is moving forward as planned.
“The aircraft’s test model did not stay on the ground longer than expected,” Baudouin said during a phone conference, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned for the aircraft’s downtime.
All manufacturers plan their tests differently.
We decided to take the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will happen throughout the flight test program.
The second of the five test samples is due to fly in the coming weeks and all others will follow soon, the company said.
Still, analysts are skeptical of the claim that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it is estimating the date of commissioning and will provide new information in the next few months.
“This slow pace of flight tests – although apparently in line with Bombardier’s internal schedule – reinforces our view that commissioning will be postponed to the first quarter of 2015,” Doerksen said.
In the third quarter, ending September 30, Bombardier’s net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same – 9 cents.
Gross income decreased slightly - from $4.2 to $4.1 billion.
Analysts expected a profit of 10 cents per share and a gross income of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world’s fourth-largest aircraft manufacturer said it delivered 45 aircraft for the quarter, down from 57 the previous year.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The aerospace department’s order portfolio was $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
“In the aerospace field, the results were consistent with our goals, but the small number of incoming orders and overall market conditions have become an unpleasant factor,” Baudouan said.
Gross revenue in the aerospace sector fell by 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest train manufacturer, said gross revenue in the sector rose nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The portfolio of orders in the transport division amounted to $ 32.6 billion as of September 30, which is slightly higher than on December 31.
The revenues of the transport division were negatively affected by the problems with the execution of several large contracts.
The management said that a new development plan will be presented in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google Chief Financial Officer Patrick Pitchett would join the board of directors, fell 8.5 percent to C$4.83 at mid-Thursday’s auction.
Brazilian company Embraer SA, the world’s third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and closest competitor to Bombardier, reported on Thursday a 10 percent reduction in quarterly revenue.
Sony expects lower annual profit
Japanese electronics manufacturer Sony, having completed the previous quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, shortened the forecast for profit for the current fiscal year.
Sony’s performance between July and September 2013 was more disappointing than expected due to a drop in demand for TVs, video cameras and personal computers produced by the Japanese corporation.
Sony’s TV business, which generated its first operating profit of 5.2 billion yen in three years in the second quarter, fell again to 9.3 billion yen in the reporting period.
The Japanese consumer electronics market is going through a difficult time, especially due to the declining demand for televisions.
