The speech gene was a stimulant of the formation of synapses
Scientists at Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein by which Foxp2’s “speech gene” performs its function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other.
The researchers found that family members had impaired the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function was not known.
In the new study, biologists have shown that at least some of its functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulant of the formation of new synapses in the brain area associated with speech formation.
This is due to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of searching for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, and only Foxp2 is responsible for its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 really affects vocalization, scientists confirmed in an experiment on mice.
When the animals’ gene activity was artificially reduced, they shouted less when parting with their mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of the sounds produced was restored.
Previously, mice also showed a link to the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals that were injected with a human copy of the gene ate more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
Until now, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, accordingly, the SRPX2 controlled by it is associated with purely "mechanical" properties of sound formation or more subtle processes.
