The lawyer’s exposure came after police investigating Scarborough’s activities found that he had been talking to Ditta regularly on the phone since February 2011.
Two detectives followed the suspect and discovered how he approached Ditt's house in Blackburn and placed the drugs of 60 percent purity in a black golf glove under the lawyer's trash cans.
Shortly after the transfer, Scarborough repeatedly called Ditta, who was at a dinner at the Ewood Park football stadium of the Blackburn Rovers team.
The lawyer returned home for drugs; there were nine conversations between them.
The court found out that Ditta was “regularly using” cocaine after tests found traces of the class A drug in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but denied cocaine use, said he spoke to a suspected dealer because he was his client, and insisted that their communication was a “lawyer secret.”
During his detention, Ditta took his wallet and tried to take out several credit cards, but all of them were confiscated, he also had a hair sample taken.
At a police interrogation, he said he had a home office, along with a job, and clients came to his home for legal reasons.
However, the court learned that after important arrests, he called the largest participants in drug trafficking, a number of which he had previously represented in court, to tell what the detectives knew about them.
In the indictment, Anne White said: “If anyone knows that you shouldn’t break the law, it’s a criminal lawyer.”
