For two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo, one of the most violent clashes since the armistice was signed more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a well-known insurgent movement that was supported first by the white Rhodesian authorities and then by the apartheid-era South African government as part of efforts to destabilize the country’s independent government.
After the 1992 armistice, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to plunge into a full-scale conflict again, but recent events have made foreign investors and locals nervous.
The stakes are high for the fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge offshore gas reserves and coal fields in the northwest could raise more than $50 billion as investments in the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the United States.
The ruling Frelimo party, a leading political force since 1975, and Renamo blame each other for the tensions.
The Renamo party claims that the government has become the instigator of the latest clashes, attacking its members in the province of Sofala, the traditional Renamo stronghold, on October 17.
Attacks on former insurgents then escalated as government troops attacked Renamo bases and attempted to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group’s leader, said Fernando Mazanga, a spokesman for Renamo, in a statement to the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating the clashes, accusing the party of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Gebuza tried to dispel concerns about instability.
Gebuza told AFP, a French news agency, on Wednesday that Mr Dhlakama felt he was a “loser” who wanted to use “everything left of his forces to try to prove that he can impose his own decisions on the government.”
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist that they want to avoid war.
However, fears grew after reports that Mazanga had announced Renamo's rejection of the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the Financial Times that he was referring to the Frelimo party’s non-compliance with the agreement.
“Our goal is to return to negotiations, but with all seriousness,” Mazanga said.
Previous negotiations between the parties have done little to ease the tensions that have been heightened by a series of clashes this year.
“These are two influential people (Gebusa and Dhlakama) facing each other’s foreheads,” said Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the Open University and an expert on Mozambique.
None of them is a good negotiator and none of them is ready to make the necessary concessions.
The Renamo party, which is trying to push for electoral reforms, has already announced that it will boycott the municipal elections scheduled for November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators interpreted this pressure as an attempt by the weakened movement to seek concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
Renamo's vote share has been declining since 1992, while the new party, the Democratic Movement of Mozambique (MDM), which was founded by a former Renamo member, is expected to improve its performance in this election.
Mr. Mazanga said that Mr. Gebuza, who was due to step down next year when his second term ended, wanted to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn’t want multi-party democracy, he doesn’t want transparent elections, he doesn’t want peace because he doesn’t want to leave the presidency,” Mazanga said.
It is unclear what capabilities Renamo has, but it has already carried out devastating and rapid attacks on police stations and cars on a key north-south highway.
Most of the skirmishes took place in the province of Sofala, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo, but includes Beira, a port that mining companies including Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of railway tracks for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railway.
Mazanga was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat the threat.
The Renamo party wanted to “warn the international community that things are not going very well in Mozambique,” Mazanga said.
Instability has intensified government dissatisfaction, and many people are also concerned about corruption, slow development and recent kidnappings, says Fernando Lima, head of independent media company Mediacoop.
“People think that the responsibility for the future of the country lies with the government and the president, who should find a solution to these problems,” he says.
Omar Sultan, a protester, said people just want stability.
“Nobody cares about Renamo or Frelimo, they just want to restore peace, they want free access to roads,” he said.
