The power engineers of Dnipropetrovsk region have started a unique program to save... nests of asts
In the old days, to bring the aists to the court, the peasants on a high pole installed a wheel from the cart, and the heavy nest was well held on it.
Such special supports have not been installed for a long time, so the aists favored the poles of power lines - the intertwined branches rely on wires, so that the aist house is reliable.
Grandmother Anya, near whose house in the village of Ivanovka Petrikovsky district for twenty years lived a true family, began to notice how the nest settles, despite all the efforts of its inhabitants.
Birds put new branches on top, and the lower layer has already passed between the wires, it is about to collapse.
Of course, it is a pity for the family of Aists, who every year nested at the yard, bred and fed for the summer three or four chicks, but even without light do not want to remain.
As soon as the birds flew to the warm regions, grandmother Anya called Tsarichansky RES, which owns the support.
I didn’t expect them to react so quickly.
When our specialists arrived in Ivanovka, they were surprised that the nest still holds, - said technical director of DTEK "Dneprooblenergo" Sergey Berezovsky.
On the wires, which were, in fact, already inside the nest, weighing 150 - 200 kilograms, began corrosion.
Birds could die from electric shock at any time.
And the locals risked being left without light due to damage to the wires.
Therefore, linear installers began an operation to save the nest, and this is not the first time in our practice.
Scientists-ornithologists from the Dnipropetrovsk National University helped, who developed a scheme for the transfer of the nest.
They also conducted trainings for employees of district networks.
The well-known Dnepropetrovsk ornithologist Alexander Ponomarenko advised power engineers at all stages of nest reconstruction.
For starters, it was estimated that there are more than 50 “apartments” in the area in an emergency state.
For their reconstruction, special metal platforms reminiscent of a funnel were welded.
The base was weaved with weed branches, and then the old nest was moved there.
According to experts, it is enough to lay old branches as a basis for the birds to recognize the nest and return to it.
After that, the squirrels will build their own homes.
A month ago, the first nest was reconstructed in the village of Peschanka of the Novomoskovsky district.
Next to the electrical support, a new reinforced concrete pillar was placed and a platform with an old, already inhabited nest was placed on it.
The entire operation cost the energy industry nine thousand hryvnias.
And the other day the same new home took place in the village of Ivanovka Petrikovsky district in the courtyard of Grandma Ani.
Here, the platform was fixed in its former place, only raised above the wires.
Ornithologists are sure that cautious, conservative birds will not even notice in the spring that their "apartment" has undergone major repairs.
Until the end of the year, the same reconstruction awaits four more nests in the Pokrovsky and Tsarichansky districts of the Dnipropetrovsk region.
By the way, while some save rare birds, others mercilessly kill them.
The other day, a sad news flew around the whole area - in the village of Ust-Kamenka of the Apostolovsky district, on the day of the opening of the hunt for pheasants, poachers shot a swan family living on the local pond for entertainment.
Noble birds were not afraid of people at all - the locals fed them and did not hurt them.
When the villagers heard the shots and ran to the pond, the four beautiful swans were already lying dead on the water.
Now employees of the Apostolovsky district police department find out who shot the birds listed in the Red Book.
The Russian March is becoming more popular.
On November 4, the Day of National Unity, the "Russian March" agreed with the city hall will be held in Moscow.
According to a poll by the Levada Center, support for the “Russian Marches” is growing - already 40% of citizens to varying degrees approve of the idea of their conduct.
According to the Levada Center, 40% of citizens to varying degrees approve of the "Russian Marches": 11% of them are definitely positive about such actions and 29% - "rather positive".
The popularity of the idea of "Russian Marches" is gradually growing - in 2006, these actions were welcomed by only 14% of Russians, and in December 2010, the holding of such events was supported by twice as many citizens (28%).
"Definitely negative" to the "Russian marches" are only 7% of Russians, "rather negative" - 19%.
Another 35% could not formulate their attitude to this action.
This year, the Moscow city hall agreed to hold a “Russian march” of up to 15,000 people in Lublin, the head of the security department of the capital, Alexey Mayorov, said today.
This nationalist event has been held every year on National Unity Day since 2005.
To the question of sociologists "Have you heard about the fact that on November 4 in Russia are held "Russian marches" under the slogans of protecting the rights of Russians in Russia?" three quarters (75%) of citizens answered in the negative.
Currently, only one in five Russians (20%) knows about this action.
It is noteworthy that in December 2010, almost a third of citizens (31%) heard about the “Russian Marches”.
Recall that three years ago on December 11, on Manege Square, a spontaneous rally of nationalists took place, which turned into mass riots.
Levada Center also asked Russians what holiday is celebrated on November 4.
In two years, the number of those who know the correct answer (National Unity Day) has increased from 41% to 49%.
However, only 15% of citizens gather to celebrate this holiday.
About the same number (17%) intend to celebrate the 7th of November Day of the October Revolution.
The majority of citizens (62%) are not going to celebrate any of these holidays.
