Obama campaign staff considered Biden's exclusion in favor of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, the closest advisers to President Barack Obama secretly considered replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton on the 2012 election list.
This discovery is the brightest sensation of all expected book by Mark Halperin and John Hailemann about the 2012 campaign "Bets Doubled: The Game Changed 2012".
The Times received a copy of the forthcoming book and reported on Thursday evening that the president’s closest aides conducted “large-scale focus group research and opinion polls in late 2011” to assess whether Biden’s exclusion could help raise fading hopes for Obama’s re-election.
According to political columnist Jonathan Martin, the book gives a detailed description of the attempt of senior officials of the campaign headquarters and the White House, namely the former head of the administration of the White house Bill Daley, to assess the effect on the vote of the appointment of former Secretary of State Clinton Vice President.
The possible replacement was a secret, carefully guarded at the Chicago campaign headquarters and the Oval Office.
Only six of the president’s closest advisers — including Daly, former Obama campaign chief Jim Messina and former senior White House advisers David Axelrod and David Pluff — knew the replacement was under consideration.
The book, Bets Doubled, claims that Daley was the initiator of an attempt to replace Biden despite their “close personal relationship,” but eventually abandoned the move when their data showed that adding Clinton to the electoral roll would not “improve Obama’s chances significantly.”
In an interview with Martin Daley, he confirmed that the administration was indeed considering replacing Biden Clinton.
“I actively advocated for a lot of things, and that was one of them,” Daley told the newspaper.
You have to remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we thought, “Oh my God, what are we supposed to do?”
Although Daly described the study as a “necessary check,” Martin told CNN’s Anderson Cooper that the campaign staff had invested enough in studying whether the move would bring dividends to the vote.
“Election headquarters don’t spend that much money on polls and focus groups unless they’re taking something seriously,” Martin told AK 360.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew that his team was considering a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he asked Daly if his then-boss knew about the possible shuffling.
Although Daly said he didn’t think the president was “aware” of a possible replacement, the former head of the administration admitted that “possibly” Obama knew.
Martin added that “bets doubled” does not give a clear answer to the question of whether the results of the political probes reached the Obama table.
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously thought Obama was unaware of the study of the possibility of removing Biden from the electoral roll.
“Perhaps,” Martin replied.
