George Kerevan: Breaking up with Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland will have to join the pan-European free movement zone as a condition for EU membership.
There are a number of stories about passport control in Berwick and the barbed-wire border along Adrian's Wall.
However, the newspaper Strathclyde pointed to the possible economic benefits of more free movement across the rest of Europe, although – predictably – it did not appear in the headlines.
Nor did anyone point out that EU member states spend a lot of time turning their formal rules around as conveniently as they can.
As Scotland is now not part of the Schengen area, continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in exchange for what it really wanted from the Scots.
So this is an unremarkable story.
And so old that it turned into a fossil: for the first time I heard the “duck” that “independence means passport control” at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting moment, lost in the retelling of an ancient fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow Europe’s orders?
Why change the yoke of London to the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the Euro crisis, the project “Europe” is officially dead.
Throughout the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or for the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining momentum.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic party Alternative for Germany – founded only this year – emerged out of nowhere and won nearly five million votes in the September federal elections, effectively ousting the Free Democrats (analogue to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been an internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency, have led many people to think that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments work with excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – something that German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself at a pre-disadvantaged disadvantage in terms of production capacity compared to Germany.
The only way out is to cut wages and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of the budget and currency is the deeper problem of Europe’s productive capacities.
As a result of a package of green energy measures implemented by Brussels — a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers — European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than in the United States.
This is paralyzingly unfavourable price conditions, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
No wage freeze in the world will stop the crushing victory of cheap U.S. shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, there is a riot, especially in France, once the most ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving France’s devastated economy in dire straits.
The result is that Marine Le Pen’s right-wing anti-EU National Front party has just won a crucial additional election, dropping the ruling Socialist Party to third place.
The Front is now France’s most popular party with 24 percent of the vote — a timely warning to British Labour that it cannot be assumed that a split among the right will automatically affect the left.
What does Le Pen do with his newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If – and this is very likely – anti-EU parties get support in this election, such a bloc will be able to take a dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
Here is my opinion: soon the growing sentiment against the EU and against the single currency in Europe will merge together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will once again become something of a vague “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several dependent economies may keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that the UK will be left unattended in the Atlantic cold.
In what position does this leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region (essentially) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland will be able to succeed under a more free European deal, provided we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating Norway's experience and preserving our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party government in Scotland is, oddly enough, the most successful political movement in Europe against austerity measures, which received an impressive majority in 2011 thanks to objections to spending cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor of the Treasury Alistair Darling and the resulting coalition of Tories and Liberal Democrats.
Scotland would now be ridiculous to vote for independence only to take the austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: aging earlier
African-American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is close
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty
The tendency to early puberty is not so pronounced in boys
Pat Eteridge, a former CNN correspondent, is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be scared if her daughter begins to form breast buds and grow pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual American Academy of Pediatrics conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring my parents — usually that doesn’t mean the rapid onset of full sexual maturity,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 in 1970.
“After the breast begins to develop, it takes at least two to three years before the menarche,” said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of “Early puberty in girls: how to deal with this common problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will progress.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but is considered "premature", when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop – this is something that the pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression can serve as a basis for tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature aging of bones, which can eventually lead to slower growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the age of the child, level of development, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is wary of drugs, but admits that “puberty suppression can mitigate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings that they are different from their peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents simply don’t want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They’re worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they’ll handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter started menstruating at age 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many popular theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys, as in girls, puberty occurs earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the premise that has the most weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls aged 6 to 9, which linked the amount of fat in the body to the terms of puberty.
Other evidence supports this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
There are various explanations.
Worldwide, early puberty appears to affect everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency towards full early puberty is not as pronounced as that of girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and children of nursery age.
“We need to be careful about how we determine the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not be ashamed to receive instructions from a pediatrician about how to talk to their child.
“This could mean an earlier than expected conversation,” Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need confirmation that even when it happens earlier than they should, this process is a normal part of life.
