New Anti-Nicotine Vaccine May Deprive Smoking of Pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes of pleasure.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests are needed before the start of human trials, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal from the medical college of Valle Cornell in New York said that the first results are encouraging.
“We very much hope that this vaccine strategy can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to overcome with these modern means,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry genetic information to produce anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a stable flow of antibodies.
Antibodies track down any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, who were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activity.
And the mice that were not given the vaccine “relaxed” and this is a sign that nicotine reached their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
To maintain a high level of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of a new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if a future human vaccine was completely safe, it could be given to children before they have a desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to stop smoking.
“They’ll know that if they start smoking again, they won’t get that pleasure from the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them get rid of that habit,” he said.
