The pawnshop owners in Singapore are doing well, while the middle class is experiencing difficulties.
At a pawnshop in the Bendemir shopping mall in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga lays down a gold bracelet, ring and earrings to pay for her daughter’s schooling.
“My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is invested there,” says Ms. Amirthalinga.
Although she earns S$3,000 ($2,400) a month as an administrator and her husband also works, her monthly family income is not enough, she says.
Indeed, demand in various parts of Southeast Asia — where household debt is rising — is such that ValueMax, where it conducts its transaction, this week became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore stock exchange.
A jewellery loan is not just a quick way to get money (S$1,300 in the case of Ms. Amirthalinga), but almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore charge an effective annual interest rate of 17% – just above the 15.4% offered in the United Overseas Bank branch, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require a credit check or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
As a result, millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel pressured by rising living costs and rapid growth in household debt and consumer debt.
After five years of sustained growth following the global financial crisis and cheap loans fueled by free monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to compensate for declining incomes as their economies slow down.
This week, Standard & Poor's, a rating agency, pointed to an increase in the family's leverage, mainly due to the growth of mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
It said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia topped the list with 80% of GDP, up from 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week barely emerged from a technical recession.
On Thursday, data showed a continued decline in exports and a weakening of consumer demand.
“The bottom line is that with prices rising, people in the middle and bottom [of the income scale] will be looking for ways to replenish their income wherever they can,” says Song Seng Woon, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Record high gold prices in the past two years have intensified the rush with which people lay down their personal belongings as they take advantage of the opportunity to get money for their family jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70% of the things laid in the 200 pawnshops of the city-state are gold products.
People say, “The price of gold looks good, so let’s put on Grandma’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
In Thailand, the largest pawnshop operator EasyMoney has seen an increase in the number of customers using its branches in recent months, up to 20%.
The growth in the pawnshop business is such that ValueMax, the operator of the branch in Bendemir and 15 others in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but also outside Asia, says Yeah Li Ching, CEO of ValueMax.
The company will fund the expansion using 60 percent of the S$66 million raised this week as a result of the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some lenders have sparked criticism due to high interest rates, Ms. Yeah says the pawnshop not only offers cheaper tariffs than other lenders, it also does not increase debt directly.
“Customers are laying down items they already own, and monetizing personal assets doesn’t increase household debt,” she says.
The institution is gaining increasing public recognition as a means to obtain short-term, secured funding.
And at the same time, pawnshops are used not only by those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Wealthy people in Singapore also use ValueMax branches by laying down gold bars or Rolex watches, which can give up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see clients from all walks of life.
“These include wealthy individuals who need to borrow short-term money for commercial projects or investments, or small businesses who need to overcome temporary monetary difficulties,” says Ms. Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
