They should not restart them until the plane reaches a height of 10,000 feet and the captain gives "good".
Passengers should turn off their devices again when the plane is descending for landing, and not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes are properly protected from electronic interference can allow passengers to use these devices during take-off, landing and steering, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft, modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at high altitudes, are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Airliners Association, welcomed these changes.
“Once the new policy is implemented safely (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this), it will be a win-win,” said Glading.
We are frankly tired of feeling “on duty at school” when it comes to this issue.
But internet connection for surfing, sharing emails, texting or downloading data will still be banned at heights below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
Thus, there is still no "Words with Friends" - an intelligent online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when there was a sensational case: the actor was removed from the plane of the airline American Airlines for refusing to turn off the device at the time when the plane was at the exit to the landing.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be put in the luggage compartment, as they can injure someone if they fly all over the cabin.
Calls from a mobile phone in flight will also be banned.
The regulatory authority for telephone calls belongs to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAU.
FAU may lift ban on some electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially create interference for navigation devices, but we know thanks to the FCC that they can create interference for cell towers when the plane is in the air,” Rosenker said.
The industry advisory committee set up by the FAU to examine the issue recommended last month that the government allow more widespread use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on FAUs to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill argue there are no compelling reasons for the bans.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure, as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
FAU began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference to navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began to carry FM radios - high-tech gadgets of the time.
New aircraft are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruise altitude for several years.
Planes modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airliners are adapted to the wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices usually emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
Devices for reading e-books, for example, emit only minimal signals when browsing pages.
But signals become more powerful when devices load or send data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on passengers' use of electronic devices was Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company downloaded the entire airliner with their Kindle e-book readers and flew on it to check for problems, but never found them.
Members of the FAU Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of the devices poses any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Air Passenger Association said he considered interference from the devices real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there were only individual pilot reports confirming that the devices could create interference for aviation systems, and most of those reports were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to require passengers to disable the devices during instrument landings in restricted visibility.
A group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a sensible step towards passengers, who now use many technological devices.
“We are pleased that FAU recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and protection,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Tourism Association.
