Is the elite of Europe ready to do business with England?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with a commitment to bring together business representatives and determine what changes wealth and jobs makers in the UK want to see in their relationship with the EU.
To this end, we ordered the largest and most comprehensive survey of British business leaders, asking them to express their thoughts on the UK, business and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders representing a wide range of businesses in the UK by size, sector and region.
The results of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses are currently looking for export opportunities outside of Europe, paying special attention to countries that are modernizing and growing, while EU countries are stagnant.
They want the government to prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil, rather than wasting time on the long and difficult process of reforming the EU’s entangled institutions.
When asked about their views on specific policy issues, from antitrust to product laws, most business leaders believed that control of these key areas of competence should be returned to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, and business representatives said that the costs of regulation from Brussels now outweigh the benefits of being in the European trade zone, even 40 percent of large enterprises, traditionally the most pro-European of all companies, agreed with this.
Last but not least, our survey of business executives revealed that a clear majority wants the UK to pursue a course of treaty change and EU relations based on trade rather than politics.
This result, which has been seen among businesses of all sizes and the largest business groups, shows that the business is insisting on a “significant change” that will bring power back to the UK.
The stakes are high – achieving treaty changes and more favourable terms for the UK will provide a 16 percent shift in voting to stay in the EU.
The prime minister should have no doubts: this poll shows that British business supports his plan to revise the terms of Britain’s EU membership.
It also shows that the business expects that the revision will lead to a significant shift in the current balance of power back towards the UK.
Better conditions for British business are possible and increasingly necessary as the eurozone embarks on a path of closer economic and financial integration.
Priority should be given to jobs and economic growth in the UK, and, as our survey shows, for businesses this means a stronger focus on trade and fundamental changes in Brussels’ regulatory performance.
