Two YMCA employees charged with sexual offences even before charges against Jonathan Lord, the Royal Commission has learned
Two employees of the YMCA NSW were charged with sexual offences against children prior to filing charges in 2011 against Jonathan Lord, a childcare worker in Karingbach, the Royal Commission on Sexual Abuse of Children reported.
But the commission’s introductory statement said it had “never dealt with cases of child sexual abuse within its organization.”
Chief Executive Officer Philip Hare was asked about one case where a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences and another case where a gym instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of sexual offences against children under his care in 1991.
Mr. Hare told Gale Ferness, a lawyer assisting the commission, that he knew of the first case but did not know of the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA also made inaccuracies in the Commission’s introductory speech, claiming that “there were external YMCA checks that acknowledged that the YMCA was at the forefront of child safety.”
The testimonials provided by the commission indicate that the YMCA has been notified that it has received the second out of four possible assessments based on the results of a quality audit performed by the Department of Education and Communities in August of this year.
Mr. Hare, who joined the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that he and the lower management had failed to hire the Lord and had not been able to ensure that staff clearly understood their obligations regarding reporting violations of child safety policies.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexual offences against 12 boys during his two years at the YMCA.
He was imprisoned for at least six years.
But Mr. Hare rejected the suggestion that YMCA’s corporate ethics prevented employees from reporting Lord’s violations of child safety.
The officers testified that they had observed violations, including that Lord was alone with the children, personally cared for them, put them on his knees, said that he loved one of them and allowed them to play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Oakwell, who was under Lord's leadership and asked to teach her to protect children because she was concerned about his behavior, testified that she found Jackie Barnat, the child custody manager of the YMCA's Karingbach branch, who was Lord's supervisor, "very intimidating and often difficult to reach."
The Executive Director said he did not accept staff explanations that it was embarrassing for them to report the situation to their senior executives.
Rather, he said, their friendship with the Lord led them away from the idea of having to report him.
Mr. Hare said that he had presented to the YMCA Council of New South Wales his opinion that the lesson for the organization from the “Accident with Jonathan Lord” was not “relating to the provision of information” by employees, and the Council agreed with him.
Mr. Hare said the decision to force employees to sign confidentiality agreements soon after the allegations appeared was made by YMCA’s director general for child custody Liam Whitley.
He said it was meant to prevent the damage of evidence, but at the same time “exaggerated” and this decision was poorly implemented.
The YMCA of New South Wales was not a child-friendly organization while Jonathan Lord was working in it between 2009 and 2011, according to the commission’s expert on child abuse, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University.
He said there were “serious problems” in recruiting, selecting, instructing, training and controlling staff.
The hearing was postponed until December 20.
