Scientists have shed light on how the dog’s tail movements are related to her mood.
Earlier studies have shown that satisfied dogs wind their tail to the right (from a dog’s point of view), while anxious dogs wave their tail mainly to the left.
But now scientists say that other members of the canine family may notice these subtle differences in howling their tails and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, says: “It is well known that people’s left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in the formation of stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at it in other species.
He added that just like humans, dogs have the right side of the brain that controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the versatile tailings of other dogs, researchers watched the animals when they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It is likely that we will soon understand why their tails are sometimes directed in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs videos of dogs — either naturalistic versions or silhouettes to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and steer the tail more left or right.”
When the animals saw that the otherwise non-expressive dog was moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the waving tail of the dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was leaning mostly to the left (again from the point of view of the waving tail of the dog), their heartbeat increased and they seemed alarmed.
Professor Vallortigara said that he does not think that dogs intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience about which movements they should worry about and which they should not.
He observes: “If there are several encounters with other dogs and often their tail is one way associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts based on this experience.”
The researchers say these findings could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal’s emotions.
Dog Behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting researcher at the University of Bristol Veterinary School, said it was not the first study to test whether the left and right sides matter to dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a satisfied dog.
In another research paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when the wagging of its tail was directed to the left instead of the right, instead of becoming alarmed — the opposite of the Italian study.”
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be helpful to study how dogs respond to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is ample evidence for different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details remain to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it is likely that we will soon understand why their tails are sometimes directed in one direction and sometimes in the other.
