The Desperation of Obama Voters
I voted for President Obama twice, sharing hope for change.
He says Obama has allowed Republican obstructionism to nullify commendable efforts.
Obstructionism cannot justify problems with the website of Obama-reformed health care system, drone attack
Obama's 2008 campaign memoirs are a sad reminder of what could have been
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year medical student at Harvard University.
I read a sad book these days.
I thought that this book would inspire me in times of despondency in the second year of medical school and revive a sense of hope in me.
It’s called “Audacity to Win,” and it’s a memoir about Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish writing reports on my patients in the evening and go to bed, this book takes me back to a time when politics has inspired millions of people and speeches have been breathtaking.
The election victory was impressive, and news anchors paused to reflect on this historic moment.
My classmates were crying with joy, and my parents kept all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of strategists was supposed to come to the White House, and the people were ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, his support rate was 82%.
Then I close the book.
Returning to the present is a crude awakening, like pulling out of a dream.
It is difficult to remember those days of optimism — they seem a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I dropped my first ballot, the changes have really happened.
It was something I couldn't even imagine.
I pay tribute to Obama for his great and diverse achievements, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act to the withdrawal of our military from Iraq, the repeal of the “Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell” rule, and the murder of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructionism has blocked too many attempts to move our country forward: immigration reform, the choice of public health, and the closure of the Guantanamo Bay base, among others.
But after countless times I’ve sided with the Obama administration, defending it against colleagues and peers, I’ve run out of explanations that I can provide.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican obstructionism cannot account for allowing foreign leaders to eavesdrop or drone strikes on innocent children in other countries.
He cannot explain the National Security Agency’s collection of data on Americans’ privacy or the prosecution of whistleblowers who expose government misconduct.
He cannot explain the killing of American citizen Anwar al-Awlaki without trial and investigation or non-compliance with government funding and spending limits during presidential campaigns.
He cannot justify the findings of the report, which states that the White House’s efforts to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And recently, it has been unable to justify failing to develop a simple website for more than three years after signing the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Should I have understood, at the age of 18, that leadership may be at odds with the political campaigns that precede it?
It is obvious that working in an elected position is not a predictable program of action, as our public dialogue will be shaped by an opposition political party and such random events as the Newtown massacre.
Nevertheless, all of the examples I have listed above show that they were largely the administration's own choice.
And that's what worries me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was an incomprehensible and rude alternative, he seemed unable to make a decision on his own politics or views.
I believed that in his second term, Obama, freed from the pressure of future elections, would justify the hopes that we have heard for such a long time.
However, when Obama’s rating fell below 45% this week, it became much more difficult to return to 2008 through this book.
It makes me miss many of the promises that have flown away.
This week I read the part of the book that describes how Clinton inflicted a deafening defeat on Obama in the Pennsylvania primary.
At a meeting to analyze the reasons for the failure, he told his employees that they should return to normal and remain true to their goal.
“I want us to return our attractiveness,” he said.
We have to remember who we are.”
It's been five years, Mr. President, and I totally agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary belong exclusively to Nathaniel Morris.
