A trip through mud, rivers and jungles to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend taking in hundreds of patients.
There are not many doctors in this West African country — only one in 5,000 people.
Vote here or via your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 main characters of CNN 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to make him CNN’s Hero of the Year.
This man will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father come back to life and relapse into unconsciousness, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that reminded him of himself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
If we had the money, we would have taken him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father for years in overcrowded clinics and hospitals, receiving whatever treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” Bwell said.
“You can leave the house at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you’re not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation has not changed much since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if the Cameroonians could go to the doctor, many of them would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health care spending is private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
And because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries.
He became a doctor and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes weekend trips to the countryside to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people are stuffed into vans, tied to rooftops, and driven across the countryside to visit the village in need of help.
They don’t always have luck.
Many times they had to push cars through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like real heroes: it is a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that the locals can offer.
Free medical care in these villages really is the reason for the holiday, and Bwelle with his wide smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join the fun.
The next morning, the brigade began to receive hundreds of patients.
“We take 500 people on every trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the county within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates — documents needed for school that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evenings, the brigade conducts simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school building, municipality, or house; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate the operating and sanitation equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
This is an impassioned pace, but the brigade’s dedication usually helps support village musicians.
“They beat the drums all night so we can stay awake and keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, members of the brigade go back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, conducted 700 free surgeries last year, and they know that their help can be of immense importance to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia surgery he received would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” he said.
In addition to these weekend clinical admissions and hospital work, surgeon Bwelle also works at night in private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this second work, he said, that provides 60% of the funding for his non-profit organization; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in Bwell’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that he can continue these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses like O’Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe to join Bwell in his quest, it’s an opportunity to practice that they would never get at home.
“We were given the opportunity to assist in surgeries where we helped remove blood stains or hold tools for Dr. Bwell,” O’Malley said.
As a second-year student, you would never get that opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medication.
But upon arrival in Yaoundé, their food, transportation, and training are paid for by Bwelle.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
To help others live a happy life, to fulfill the promise given to his father, is what brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle said.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see what you can do to help.
