The Agency "Rosbalt" was deprived of the status of the media for obscene fighting
On October 31, the Moscow City Court decided to invalidate the license on the registration of the agency "Rosbalt", - writes "Lenta".
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of media status - for systematic and gross violations of the law on media.
During the process, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, in fact denying the publication the right to put forward counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
CJSC "Rosbalt Information Agency" was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has been developing and operating as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was included in the list of the most recognizable private online media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency’s exclusive publications were (and still are) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the closeness of the publication to the law enforcement agencies continued throughout the existence of the agency.
Along with the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive database of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions, it was also said that Natalia Chaplina, the wife of Viktor Cherkesov, was at the head of the project.
At the same time, Chaplin’s role in Rosbalt’s leadership is not entirely clear: she is often called the “project manager”.
The general director of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt has not appeared in the ratings of the federal media - neither in terms of citation nor in terms of audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the ranking of the attendance of Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are notes about the Kremlin's helplessness in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group "King and Shout", the pogroms in the capital Biryulev.
The Rosbalt conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the law on the media came into force, prohibiting journalists from obscene warfare.
The agency found the forbidden vocabulary in two videos published on the agency's website ("Jigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot desecrated oil towers").
The following pages are described differently.
Roskomnadzor, on the basis of the detected video materials, accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the law on the media and appealed to the court with a demand to take away the license from the agency.
Rosbalt stated that the claims of the department are illegal: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the native words in them were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor’s claims in the peace court – and when on October 22, 2013, the Moscow City Court accepted the claim of Roskomnadzor, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, on the 25th day, the world judge made a decision not in favor of Rosbalt: editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code on administrative offenses and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court – if you give up the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the certificate of registration of Rosbalt, effectively depriving the agency of the status of the media.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt was left alone during this confrontation.
The Agency was supported by deputies of the State Duma (the statement to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted on the initiative of the Communist Party of Russia).
The head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Council on Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov stated about the illegality of the closure of the publication.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even provided him with some guarantees that the case will not come to the withdrawal of the license.
The trial of Rosbalt showed that under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be the media in Russia today is a big question.
