He then became the first senior U.S. government member to admit that U.S. espionage went too far, but stressed that no one’s rights had been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it has gone unreasonably far.
And the president is determined to shed light on this issue and explain himself to people, and is now conducting a thorough analysis to ensure that no one has a sense of abuse.
I assure you, there are no abuses against innocent people in this process.”
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA acted with good intentions and that his surveillance operations saved many lives.
He added: “We are working in a new world where people are willing to blow themselves up.
There is radical extremism in the world, reckless and determined to kill people, blow people up and attack governments.
What if you were able to intercept it, stop it before it happens?
We were actually preventing plane crashes, building explosions and killing people because we were able to learn about these plans in advance.”
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will head to Europe to help resolve issues related to alleged U.S. espionage abroad and convince Europeans to continue joint anti-terrorism activities with the U.S., the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs chair said on Thursday.
Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy said he spoke with members of the European Parliament and others this week and is concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorist organizations due to frustration over surveillance conducted by the National Security Agency.
“It is really important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans remain our supporters in our common anti-terrorism efforts,” said Democrat Murphy, who is in his first term as chairman of the Senate’s Subcommittee on International Relations for European Affairs.
“And I’m going to Europe to make it clear to them that we must continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger at these NSA programs.”
News that the NSA has collected millions of phone records in Europe has worsened relations with some U.S. allies, although the agency’s head said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected a misunderstanding of metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the United States.
Other revelations cited documents released by Snowden, indicating that the NSA monitored the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel, as well as the phones of about 34 other world leaders.
National Intelligence Director James Clapper defended espionage against allies as necessary and said it was common on both sides.
Against this backdrop, Murphy said his office is organising a trip for members of Congress, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hopes the delegation will include members of both parties and both houses.
The names of the other participating legislators should be announced in the coming days.
According to him, the program of the trip is still in the development stage.
Although Murphy said the purpose of the trip was to help improve relations, he said some degree of “best-intentioned toughness” would also be manifested.
He said European leaders should be honest with their people about what spying programs they have used for years.
“While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they also have to agree with the fact that we are not the only ones engaged in intelligence activities,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry is due to head to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to address hostility to U.S. strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. intelligence activities.
