Australian woman appeals against jail term in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney woman sentenced to 15 days in prison on Phuket island for falsely claiming to have been attacked by a taxi driver appealed the sentence and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty by the Phuket Provincial Court on June 15 of filing a false claim after Thai police reported that a local taxi driver had carried out the attack on Sunday, June 10, while two other men were holding her.
However, CCTV footage later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after breaking up with her Australian boyfriend.
The Phuket police questioned Bamford for two days before she confessed to fabricating the story.
Before the trial, she was held in local police cells.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison sentence at a detention center for general detainees on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than at an adult women's prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian League player Peter Tanks, who turned to the Foreign Office in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tanks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about her daughter’s well-being and was waiting for her to return to Australia.
“Obviously it was an alarming time, but we hope she will return home safely as soon as possible,” Tanks said.
Bamford appealed her sentence and was released on bail of 50,000 baht.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently spending her vacation in the Krabi resort area in southern Thailand.
Legal sources in Thailand reported that Bamford is currently representing a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could lead to the court increasing her sentence by up to two years and forcing her to serve an adult prison sentence.
However, after the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore its eroded tourist image, leading to an acquittal.
